body:
It seems that the following limit exists. But I couldn't figure out the exact value. Anyone could help me? Thanks!
\begin{align*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow 0^{+}} {\sum_{n=1} ^{\infty} \frac{\sqrt{t}}{1+tn^2}}
\end{align*}

I have some problems, with the convergence of this sequence defined recursively. It's clear that it's bounded. But is it convergent? How can I check for convergence? $$ a_0 = a_1 = 1 $$ $$
a_n  = a_{a_{n - 1} }  + a_{n - a_{n - 1} } 
$$ How do I prove that the sequence $\frac{a_n}{n}$ converges? I tried but am not able to do it.
